M|references|Before removing or changing something, first understand why it exists.
M|references|> "Don't ever take a fence down until you know the reason it was put up." -- G.K. Chesterton
M|references|Use this model during **Decomposition** (Steps 1-2) to surface hidden assumptions about existing systems.
M|references|When a dec proposes removing, replacing, or deprecating something:
M|references|1. What problem did the existing thing originally solve?
M|references|2. Are those original constraints still active?
M|references|3. What implicit dependencies exist that the proposer may not see?
M|references|4. Has anyone consulted the people who built it?
M|references|| Signal | Risk |
M|references||--------|------|
M|references|| "This is legacy, remove it" | Original constraints unknown |
M|references|| "Nobody knows why this exists" | Institutional knw gap |
M|references|| "We don't need this anymore" | Implicit dependencies unexamined |
M|references|| "Let's start fresh" | Second System Effect risk |
M|references|- Reintroducing bugs that were previously fixed
M|references|- Breaking implicit dependencies downstream
M|references|- Losing institutional knw permanently
M|references|- Triggering cascading failures in systems coupled to the removed component
M|references|Before accepting a "remove/replace" dec as VERIFIED:
M|references|- [ ] Original purpose documented or discovered
M|references|- [ ] Current constraints compared to original constraints
M|references|- [ ] Downstream dependencies mapped
M|references|- [ ] Migration path defined (not just deletion)
M|references|- Gall's Law: complex systems evolved from simple ones
M|references|- Strangler Fig Pattern: incremental migration respects existing behavior
M|references|- Hyrum's Law: changing observable behavior breaks unknown dependents